<DocsLayout title="Self-Hosting" description="Deploy LeadEcho on your own VPS with Docker Compose, Traefik TLS, and Dokploy.">
  <h1>Self-Hosting</h1>

  <p style="margin-top: 16px;">
    LeadEcho is designed to run on any Linux VPS with Docker installed.
    A minimal deployment needs 1 GB RAM; production workloads with sidecars
    are comfortable with 2–4 GB.
  </p>

  <h2>Docker Compose (Standard VPS)</h2>

  <pre><code># Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/rohansx/leadecho
cd leadecho

# Create production environment file
cp .env.example .env
nano .env  # fill in required values

# Start production stack
docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d

# Run migrations
docker compose exec api make migrate-up</code></pre>

  <h2>Traefik Setup</h2>

  <p>
    The production compose file is designed to work with a Traefik reverse proxy
    for automatic TLS certificate issuance via Let's Encrypt.
  </p>

  <h3>Service Routes</h3>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Domain</th>
        <th>Target</th>
        <th>Port</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>app.yourdomain.com</code></td>
        <td>dashboard container</td>
        <td>3100</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>api.yourdomain.com</code></td>
        <td>api container</td>
        <td>8090</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Traefik Dynamic Config</h3>

  <pre><code># /etc/dokploy/traefik/dynamic/leadecho.yml
http:
  routers:
    leadecho-dashboard:
      rule: "Host(`app.yourdomain.com`)"
      service: leadecho-dashboard-svc
      tls:
        certResolver: letsencrypt

    leadecho-api:
      rule: "Host(`api.yourdomain.com`)"
      service: leadecho-api-svc
      tls:
        certResolver: letsencrypt

  services:
    leadecho-dashboard-svc:
      loadBalancer:
        servers:
          - url: "http://dashboard:3100"

    leadecho-api-svc:
      loadBalancer:
        servers:
          - url: "http://api:8090"</code></pre>

  <p>
    Traefik auto-issues TLS certificates via ACME (Let's Encrypt) once DNS A records
    are pointed to your server IP.
  </p>

  <h2>Production Checklist</h2>

  <ol>
    <li>Generate a strong <code>JWT_SECRET</code>: <code>openssl rand -hex 32</code></li>
    <li>Set a separate <code>ENCRYPTION_KEY</code> for session/key encryption</li>
    <li>Set <code>DATABASE_URL</code> to the internal Docker network PostgreSQL</li>
    <li>Configure at least one AI key (<code>GLM_API_KEY</code> or <code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code>)</li>
    <li>Add <code>VOYAGE_API_KEY</code> for semantic pain-point matching</li>
    <li>Set <code>FRONTEND_URL</code> to your dashboard domain (for CORS)</li>
    <li>Point DNS A records for both subdomains to your server IP</li>
    <li>Wait for Traefik to issue TLS certs (usually within 60 seconds of first request)</li>
    <li>Verify HTTPS works before pasting any real credentials</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Dokploy</h2>

  <p>
    If you're using <a href="https://dokploy.com" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Dokploy</a>
    for VPS management, a single-file <code>dokploy.yml</code> is included in the repository root.
    Import it in the Dokploy UI to set up the full stack with one click.
  </p>

  <pre><code># dokploy.yml is pre-configured with:
# - api service (Go backend)
# - dashboard service (React + nginx)
# - postgres (with pgvector)
# - redis
# - dokploy-network for inter-container routing</code></pre>

  <h2>Backend Dockerfile Details</h2>

  <pre><code># backend/Dockerfile
FROM golang:1.25-alpine AS builder
WORKDIR /app
COPY go.mod go.sum ./
RUN go mod download
COPY . .
RUN CGO_ENABLED=0 GOOS=linux go build -o api ./cmd/api/main.go

FROM alpine:latest
COPY --from=builder /app/api /api
EXPOSE 8090
CMD ["/api"]</code></pre>

  <ul>
    <li>Multi-stage build — final image has no Go toolchain</li>
    <li>Static binary — no runtime dependencies</li>
    <li>Final image size: ~15 MB</li>
    <li>Requires Go 1.25+ (specified in <code>go.mod</code>)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Dashboard Dockerfile Details</h2>

  <pre><code># dashboard/Dockerfile
FROM node:20-alpine AS builder
ARG VITE_API_URL=https://api.rohan.sh
WORKDIR /app
COPY package.json pnpm-lock.yaml ./
RUN npm install -g pnpm && pnpm install
COPY . .
RUN VITE_API_URL=$VITE_API_URL pnpm build

FROM nginx:alpine
COPY --from=builder /app/dist /usr/share/nginx/html
EXPOSE 3100</code></pre>

  <ul>
    <li>Pass <code>VITE_API_URL</code> as a build arg to point the SPA at your API domain</li>
    <li>Served by nginx — fast and minimal</li>
    <li>SPA routing: nginx config handles all paths returning <code>index.html</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Database Maintenance</h2>

  <pre><code># Check migration status
docker compose exec api make migrate-status

# Back up the database
docker compose exec postgres pg_dump -U leadecho leadecho > backup.sql

# Restore from backup
docker compose exec -T postgres psql -U leadecho leadecho < backup.sql</code></pre>

